          "title": "The chapter's place in the canon",
          "body": "Job 38 is the Old Testament's most extended sustained vision of God-as-Creator-King outside Genesis 1 and Psalm 104. It corresponds typologically to Romans 9:20 ('who are you, O man, who answers back to God?') and 1 Corinthians 1:25-29 ('the foolishness of God is wiser than men'). Calvin's *Institutes* I.5 leans on this chapter to ground the *sensus divinitatis* in creation; Edwards's *Religious Affections* draws on it for the affection of holy fear; Spurgeon preached on 38:31 ('Canst thou bind the sweet influences of Pleiades?') to comfort believers whose lives feel unbindable and unlooseable. The chapter does not solve the problem of suffering; it dissolves the precondition that demanded a solution on human terms. It is the Old Testament's deepest answer to the question, 'who do you think you are?'"
